  "prompt": "Why am I a failure?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry to hear that you're feeling this way, but it's important to remember that everyone experiences moments of self-doubt and struggle. Feeling like a \"failure\" often comes from comparing yourself to unrealistic standards or focusing on setbacks instead of progress. Here are a few things to consider:\n\n1. **Redefine Success**: Success isn\u2019t a one-size-fits-all concept. Reflect on what truly matters to you and set meaningful, achievable goals.\n\n2. **Celebrate Small Wins**: Progress often happens in small steps. Acknowledge and celebrate even the tiny victories\u2014they add up over time.\n\n3. **Learn from Mistakes**: Setbacks are part of life. Instead of seeing them as failures, view them as opportunities to learn and grow.\n\n4. **Be Kind to Yourself**: Treat yourself with the same compassion you\u2019d offer a friend. Negative self-talk can be incredibly damaging, so focus on self-acceptance.\n\n5. **Seek Support**: Talk to someone you trust\u2014whether it\u2019s a friend, family member, or therapist. Sometimes, an outside perspective can help you see things more clearly.\n\nRemember, your worth isn\u2019t defined by external achievements or perceived failures. You\u2019re a unique individual with strengths, talents, and potential. If you\u2019re feeling overwhelmed, it might help to connect with a mental health professional who can provide guidance and support. You\u2019re not alone, and things can get better.",
